The author recalls an experience, when he stayed up late into the night, reading one of Crowley's works, and a black cat entered through the window and jumped into his lap, making him wonder if perhaps it was Crowley himself reincarnated as a cat.

Evola laughs at the suggestion, saying Crowley would instead reincarnate as a rat or weasel. Then he explains surely the cat was merely looking for company, as they are social creatures, and says he hopes the author had not scared it. Things in life are often only as they seem.
